ructive habits, including cutting, and eventually to a corrupt for-profit mental hospital in which she spent eighteen months tied to a bed. She explains how boxing became her salvation as an adult; she learned how to turn her anger and aggression into motivation to train hard and excel at her sport, not only becoming the first woman to fight as a professional in a sanctioned fight in New York, but also fighting more ten-round fights than any other woman in history. A gripping account of Zamarron's 2005 upset win over Maribel Zurita to claim her second world championship caps the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBoxers (Sports) -- United States -- Biography. 0aBoxers (Sports)zUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen boxers -- United States -- Biography. 0aWomen boxerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aZamarron, Anissa. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Sports.2bisacsh1 aZamarron, Anissa "The Assassin".40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292793385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292793385/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK